,Not Recommended,214250,21604775,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,Jack Muskrat,"In my opinion, this game missed out on so much. You're brought into a world/environment that could be rife with background and stories but somehow they manage to leave you (or me, at least) feeling both wanting to know more about it and also not caring about what is told about what happened. A lot fo the comments about whatever took place feel like a passing explanation - as if no thought has been put into it and just trying to brush it off.The main character's story/search feels COMPLETELY dismissed for 95% of the game. I can understand being a character that wants to help people but when it comes to the point of getting home and not finding what you wanted, right there it seems to be thrown onto the backburner. The character says now and then ""Oh I'm here doing this"" - NO YOU'RE NOT! You get thrown on everyone else's errands. When it does loop back to the point he is going to continue onto his search, I found I just couldn't care less anymore.When it comes to the controls, they just seem...off. I kept finding myself climbing down onto ledges without meaning to, not being able to jump down or climb up when I NEEDED to - leading to me dying. Or aiming at an enemy and suddenly it aims at the one without the gun, or on one occassion I found I died because while trying to aim at a particular enemy the auto-aim just kept looping through the FOUR that were closing in on me. And it's so very repetitive! There's so much climbing that it just ends up with no tension as your stamina decreases because you've seen/heard it a million times, and it just feels like a chore. I thought things would get more interesting when they brought in the rope-swing but found it only gets used a couple of times, and then it's so stiff and lifeless that it just sucks you out of the game further.I've actually recorded this as a series on my YT channel and the honest reason I continued it until the end was how ridiculous it was trying to do anything. Parts were rage-inducing, but mostly it was laughable at how stupid it all seemed. I'm glad I played through it just so I know how rubbish I found it, but I would recommend others to just go onto YouTube and watch it. Or if you are going to buy it, make sure it's on one hell of a sale."
76561198083938339,Recommended,214250,26140063,"Posted: 20 October, 2016",all,Mog,"The game was good for its time. It came out on March 7, 2012. The Last of Us came out on June 14, 2013. Some people say this game is a wannabe of The Last of Us, but I do not see how that is possible. The storylines and gameplay are different from one another. What I like the best about the game was that you had to think about how you were going to take down your enemies with limited supplies. I did not like seeing the stamina gauge at the top of the screen during every second of gameplay. I would have liked it to show only when in use. I played this game on Windows 8 with no problems. I wish there was sequal to this game with updated game play. Achievments/trophies  are not supported by Steam, but there is a trophy system in the game itself. The Playstation 3 version does support trophies."
,Recommended,214250,23703134,"Posted: 22 June, 2016",all,The Horror Network | Embalmer,"When you think of developer/publisher Ubisoft, you don't typically think of post-apocalyptic survival games. I Am Alive was originally under development by Darkworks from 2003-2007, before Ubisoft Shanghai stepped in and took the reins and completed the project. It was then released for Xbox Live Arcade, Playstation Network, and PC in 2012.It has been one year since ""The Event"" happened in North America, and the world is a war-torn dystopian place that is filled with deadly gangs and deranged psychopaths who will stop at nothing to slaughter you for your few worldly possessions. You take the role of an unnamed lone male survivor, who has set out to find his daughter Mary and wife Linda in their hometown of Haventon. Very early in the game you arrive at your old apartment, only to discover that your family has fled to safety. While you play the game in a mostly third-person perspective, the cutscene events are told through the man's camcorder where he films himself at various intervals. The plot further unfolds by helping other survivors by supplying them with items that they need, and in exchange you receive bits and pieces of the story.There is a heavy emphasis on climbing as the main game mechanic. You have two bars atop your screen; the one to the left is your stamina meter, and the one to the right indicates your health. Everything but walking in I Am Alive requires the use of stamina; running, climbing, staying still while climbing, and even fighting. If you do any of these things for too long, and your stamina depletes entirely, you will have a quick-time-event (QTE) prompt which you must keep mashing in order not to fall. However, this QTE will not last forever, and when time is up and you are not in a safe location, you will fall to your death. Upon reaching the QTE, your stamina capacity diminishes, and you must consume varying food and drink to recover it.There are also sections that are filled heavily with dust, as The Event keeps causing earthquakes that constantly stir up soot, ash, plaster, and other debris from the destroyed urban landscape. These dust filled areas cause your stamina to continually drain, until you can climb up out of the dust cloud to recover. It's these sections that are incredibly time consuming to traverse, and it's very difficult to be on the lookout for survival items as the density of the dust cloud causes severely weakened visibility. It can be very frustrating at times, especially if you've lost your bearings (despite the map that you're equipped with), or do not have any items to recover your stamina. However, it's the key element that drives the exploration and survival factor of the overall game.Emphasized as a secondary mechanic, fighting can at times also be tedious. While you spend the rest of the game roaming around in third-person view, when you draw your bow or gun you are thrown into first-person; this can be a little disorienting at first, and you need to make sure that you know who you are aiming at prior to engaging in combat. If you aim at an enemy with a gun, he will undoubtedly shoot first and ask questions later, Many a death has been attributed to not realizing if a foe has a gun or not, as from a distance the texture and model is indistinguishable. There are also areas where you will encounter groups of enemies, some of which will appear out of nowhere behind you. Bullets are a precious and invaluable commodity, and reservation of ammunition use is highly advised. Many times you may be better off simply hacking the gang members apart with your machete, although you'll only succeed in this manner in a one-on-one standoff.The aforementioned gameplay focuses bring me to talk about the Retry system. If you're playing on a difficulty beyond that of Easy, you will use up one Retry for every death you take. You gain Retries by successfully completing an area, and helping out other survivors. If you run out of Retries, you have to start again from the beginning of the entire chapter. This can cause the 4-6 hours of normal game time to extend even further, depending on just how agile and cautionary your play style is. Even for a 2012 title, the graphics are exceedingly sub-par for the time period. They look about as good as the end-generation of games for the Playstation 2, and remind me very much of Resident Evil 4. Though given the price and length of the game, this minor fault can easily be forgiven and overlooked. There's also not really much of a soundtrack to talk about, unless you count the very annoying stamina meter depletion warning music.I Am Alive is, all in all, a solid older post-apocalyptic adventure game. The climbing sections are just as strenuous as they are enjoyable, and while the combat may be overwhelming at times, it really is satisfying to kick enemies off ledges, into fire, and put an arrow through someones eye socket. The controls can, at times, be a little wonky and hard to work with, but once you get the hang of it, you won't want to put this title down until you finish it. Other reviewers have claimed that they've experienced crashes with the title, but I never experienced any issues whatsoever. This one is highly worth checking out, but I would advise to wait for a decent discount or a price drop.Rating:4.0/5.0- Excellent, highly worth playing.The Horror NetworkCurator|GroupClick for Gore"
