76561198009735475,Not Recommended,214250,9721076,"Posted: 4 April, 2014",all,rayzobho,"Cool idea: a post-apocalyptic survival game with linear gameplay like Prince of Persia, but more puzzle-y... unfortunately the gamepad support is irreparably broken and the game is buggy as hell.  I sort of regret having bought this."
,Not Recommended,214250,11602219,"Posted: 8 August, 2014",all,Polterpneuma,"First off, I would like to state that I have yet to complete this game out of sheer frustration.Though I will keep on attempting to finish the game,granted if I can win the race between me finishing the game and my controller breaking.That being said, here are my two cents about this game.I will start off with the bad side of the game in order to create a critique that feels like you are eating a pudding with glazed sugar layered at the bottom, where the further you go and eat in more of the chunks, the sweeter it gets.I Am Alivewas once an extremely anticipated game when it was first leaked on 2009, and announced to be completed on 2010, but was later pushed back several times before finally being released on 2012. This gave potential buyers the time to ponder about the game.When news first befell unto my ears, I heard so many rumors that this game would become the ultimate open world survival game with a good storyline to follow through. However, like any fairly hyped games, you are bound to be disappointed.The final product released into the market looked like a stillbirth compared to what people were expecting from the game.As a result, the game's popularity sank faster than a fat lady trying to water skii whilst wearing lead shoes.Granted, this is not entirely the developers' fault, as speculations may have created greater expectation, but could be easily diminished by not being so hush about the game's situation and deliver actual information and updates rather than popping up ever so often just to deliver push-backs.Over the course of some five hours of me playing this game, I can sum up the game in three words, ""Trial and error.""By using new players' naiveté, the game would constantly throw you into situations where you are required to know beforehand what you are facing, to which usually results in death, and because of the limited retry system, this is like someone giving you a slap in the face and then proceeded to light your head on fire, as the system adds more than a big slap to the face, to which I will elaborate in a moment. I have found myself setting the game to the easiest difficulty to allow myself to go through all the death hoops the game presents to me with my trial and error technique in order to become acquainted with said death hoops, just so I would not light myself on fire on the normal playthrough.The second thing is the delusion of difficulty, not illusion, but delusion. For some reason, the developer thought that simply by limiting the amount of retries the player can have in a trial and error game, the game would be interesting and challenging. If that were the case, then Honey Boo Boo's mother is a supermodel, and telling people to limit the amount of times they can urinate a day is a good idea.Look, we have all gone through the age where that formula worked, where you played, died, and subsequently receive a game over screen. That was when the existing technology limited the amount of content that could be present in the game, and so by using that retry formula, the consumers would have the illusion of getting their money's worth. I have had my fair share ofContraandGhouls 'n Ghostsalready back in the days, I want to be able to play a game that would not tell me how many times I could go pee-pee in the waterbowl.The three things I also absolutely hated in this game are: The grappling hook mechanic, the death conditions, and the bullet scarcity formula. When I first acquired the grappling hook, it was a complete nightmare for me. The swining momentum is just so bad that it makes swimming through a tub full of mayonaise seem that much easier. It took me seven tries before I could finally get the gist of it and finally not fall off and become the next cannibal's grand slam. Talking about falling and dying a horrible death, I never understood how the main character sometimes manages to die from a half-meter drop. Those areas obviously have absolutely nothing there, and if I were sliding, my momentum was just about enough to rub a gum off of my shoe, but yet, those spots still somehow manage to kill me. Perhaps messing up the sliding gave the main character so much emotional distress that he died of pure embarrassment.Within any survival games, I am one of those players that tend to hoard anything that I can find and use as little of them as possible, this game was no exception, but what definitely has gotten to me was the fact that the game will attempt to, in any manner and time as physically possible, to keep your bullet count around one or two. Now, this may sound like an excellent mechanic, and I am the one who is whining about something mundane, but the fact that any time you kill a gun-wielding assailant with two or more bullets in your possession, the gun you get from them is always empty, really ticks me off. However, if some other baddie picks up the gun, he would start shooting up the place like a twelve year old kid playing Rookie Mode onResident Evil 2. This is not a good mechanic, this only manages to show the player a huge sign written thusly, ""You are in my pistol theme park, and you will never have more bullets than I want you to."" Why bother doing the whole survival aspect when you are not letting me worry about using resources? Since I know for a fact that I will always get bullets somewhere for a necessary fight ahead of me.Talking about bullets and fights, the staticity and linearity is absolutely flabbergasting. You would think that despite not being the ultimate open world survival game,I Am Alivewould still provide the fundementals of the genre, right?Wrong.For the majortiy, if not all, of the cases, there is only one way to climb to the destination, only one way to swing somewhere with the swing hook, and only one way to defeat foes. There are some hidden items here and there given out for looking a bit further, but would also usually mean wasting precious foodstuffs and dying; they might as well place big pieces of paper with, ""I owe you, invalid upon death,"" all over it, as this was mentioned to be a trial and error game with limited tries.As for its staticity, every event and item placement are always at exactly the same place, even with static events, you would at least expect non-static placements for loots, and hope that perhaps that one time when you recheck that mundane corner again, a flashing item surrounded by an white aura would appear, like a young kid hoping to findNarniain their grandmother's wardrobe, only to find an abundent amount of mothballs located within.Oh, and the save system sucks harder than an industrial grade vacuum cleaner.Despite so many factors, including the menu being complete and utter stinking fecal matter, that make this game so frustrating, I cannot get myself to hate this game.All in all, I am just so very intrigued by the world, the environment, and the idea of this game.Despite the frustrationI Am Alivemakes me deal with, during the immersive moments of the game, when I truly looked, especially into the story and the world, this game makes me feel in awe, and delivers so many other emotional impacts, like a pyromaniac seeing a forest on fire for the first time (to which the aforementioned person may or may not have been the cause of).I realize that I am on my own in the broken world.I realize that this game is not be for everyone, hence I would not recommend this game.However, if you are willing to overlook the many flaws I have already pointed out, and the ones I may have forgotten about, go ahead and try it out, but I do not in any way guarentee a frustration-free playthrough.TL;DR:You most likely will not like it, but if you are willing to look at the game in a different perspective, by all means, go for it."
,Not Recommended,214250,12763869,"Posted: 3 November, 2014",all,gobbo,"I really wanted to give this game a try, but it seems to be fighting back.There is NO FOV SETTING in the game, so if you tend to suffer from motion sickness induced by low FOV, this is not your game. There are hacks available, though. On the plus side, the game does not appear to have motion blur.There are several issues with the game, such as the controls not remappable separately, but only as a group (e.g. ""Drop/Draw Weapon""). And since ""Fire"" and ""Run"" are in the same group, that is really annoying.Another issue (and ultimately the one that leads me to not recommending the game) is that the game streams in world data, and when it does that, it sometimes stops responding to mouse input. This can go away within moments, but on occasion it stays. As a result, your mouse cursor will be fixed to the centre of the screen, in menus as well as in Windows when tabbed out. Even killing the game process doesn't seem to fix it, only a system reboot will do.I tried to like the game, but it's just not enjoyable."
