76561198063489194,Recommended,214250,15031420,"Posted: 24 March, 2015",all,Tigresuave11,"For all of it's flaws, it does pull you in and make you feel like you're really a normal person trying to survive in a inhospitable landscape surrounded (I use the term losely) by people who are trying to do the same. The washed out landscape with obstructed view makes you feel alone and the limited supplies really make you helpless. I also think it was the first time I felt really guilty about killing someone. The first guy you kill in the game wasn't necessarily an evil guy, just a guy who was scared and at the end of his rope. Everything just happens so fast (for me at least) and at the end, I thought, did I just kill a guy? Maybe its cause there is no tangible reward, but I didn't feel good about it. Even when I had to take out the guys who are after the little girl (who really deserved it) didn't make me feel like I did something great, just that I did what had to be done. I really started to care about what happened to that little girl and worried that if I was gone for too long, something would happen to her. The way the game makes you feel like that without openly shaming you or giving you some kind of morality meter made it feel real. It you want that kind of feeling, and aren't easily frustrated (because the game does not hold your hand at all and managing resources/failing to plan ahead is punishing), give it a try."
